<TEXT>
poles voted sunday in the freest elections 
in the east bloc in 42 years with solidarity confident of success 
and the communist party braced for a feared poor showing 
poles living under the communist system since the end of world 
war ii began voting at 6 am for a senate in which solidarity 
candidates are running for all 100 seats 
opposition and independent candidates also were allowed to run 
for 161 of the 460 seats in the sejm or parliament the polls were 
to close at 10 pm 
surveys projected that 80 percent of the nations 27 million 
eligible voters would cast ballots the national election 
commission said final results might not be available until 
wednesday or thursday 
thousands of polish immigrants filed absentee ballots saturday 
at polish consulates in new york chicago and washington 
this is pure satisfaction said jack piotrowski 38 of 
butler nj who came to america six years ago and cast his ballot 
in new york city 
im a bit surprised said tomasz zalewski 41 of brooklyn 
an official poll watcher for solidarity i didnt expect such a 
turnout 
a consular official in new york said 5000 people had registered 
to vote and by 3 pm saturday 3500 people had cast ballots in 
chicago thousands of poles braved thunderstorms and hourlong waits 
to vote 
solidarity leader lech walesa was cheered saturday night at a 
tumultuous rally outside his modest home in the port city of 
gdansk we showed the world we can fight now lets show we can 
do things peacefully he said 
more than 500 cars drove by filled with solidarity supporters 
who flashed the vforvictory sign 
walesa held a private party at his home before the rally and the 
house was filled with wellwishers president george bush is 
scheduled to have lunch there with walesa and his family when the 
us leader visits gdansk in july 
this is a rehearsal for bushs visit walesa told the 
associated press with a hearty laugh 
if 80 percent of the voters cast ballots it will be one of the 
highest turnouts in years a national referendum in 1987 on 
political and economic reform drew 673 percent of the voters in 
elections in june 1988 for local and provincial councils the 
government reported a 56 percent turnout 
relatively free elections occurred in poland in 1947 with some 
opposition but the communist party won the balloting and 
established complete political control 
solidarity has taken numerous steps to try to ensure sundays 
election is honest 
opposition representatives serve on commissions conducting the 
elections and solidarity recruited more than 100000 poll watchers 
at solidarity headquarters saturday workers scrambled to 
identify polling places and set up an unofficial vote tabulation 
system 
communist party leader wojciech jaruzelski in a tv address 
friday night stressed accommodation and said the party would be 
interested in forming a broad postelection coalition 
walesa an interview taped for broadcast saturday night urged 
restraint saying too much emotion could frighten the other side 
and destroy us 
lastminute campaign skirmishes continued saturday a party 
spokesman accused solidarity of rejecting a moratorium on 
campaigning saturday and sunday 
but the union denied there was such a proposal and solidarity 
candidates held rallies as rain drenched warsaw 
while the senate voting is fully democratic the existing 
parliament made up of one chamber called the sejm will remain 
in the control of the party by virtue of a deal authorities made 
with the solidarityled opposition on april 5 
independent candidates were permitted to run for 161 or 35 
percent of the 460 sejm seats the rest were reserved for 
candidates from the party and its allies 
but the party could end up with fewer seats than the 65 percent 
expected if voters reject the national list of 35 prominent 
politicians running unopposed the list includes no 2 in the 
party jozef czyrek prime minister mieczyslaw f rakowski and 
interior minister czeslaw kiszczak 
if the national list candidates do not receive at least 50 
percent of the vote their seats will not be filled 
it is possible the communists could have only a threevote 
majority when the sejm and senate convene to choose a president 
next month 
party leaders in the last days of the campaign stressed that the 
national list candidates should be elected for the sake of the 
april agreement 
when one appeals to cross out the national list then the 
campaign becomes a confrontation party secretary stanislaw 
ciosek said saturday 
czyrek said rejection of the list could lead to a constitutional 
impasse that might have to be resolved in court because the 
constitution says the sejm should have 460 members 
as part of the april agreement between the government and the 
opposition solidarity regained legal status after a sevenyear ban 
imposed during a martial law crackdown in december 1981 
</TEXT>
