<TEXT>
a former us hostage in iran said the death of the ayatollah 
ruhollah khomeini ends a nightmare for the former captives and for 
the islamic republic itself and opposition figures sunday 
predicted major changes in iran 
im not the type to say im happy hes dead said former 
hostage barry rosen one of the 52 hostages held 444 days by 
radical iranian students from 1979 to 1981 but i do feel to a 
certain degree that that part of the nightmare is over for us and 
for iran 
a former president of the islamic republic abolhassan 
banisadr likened khomeinis death to the death of spanish 
dictator franco and said it could mean iran would like spain 
turn toward democracy 
the dictatorship is at an impasse in iran banisadr said 
iran made a revolution for democracy there is no other solution 
for iran but democracy 
khomeini 86 died 12 days after undergoing surgery for bleeding 
in his digestive system according to the official iranian news 
agency 
for those iranians who followed and worshipped him as a 
religious leader its a tremendous tragedy but i dont see his 
death as a tragedy i see the tragedy in him coming to power at 
that time in irans history said rosen assistant to the 
president of brooklyn college 
he had his own moral standards i think he hurt millions of 
people not just outside of iran but many iranians have died because 
of khomeini he has caused a lot of pain all over the world 
rosen said 
banisadr said khomeinis death opened three possibilities a 
war of succession power held by a troika of parliament speaker 
abolhassan rafsanjani president ali khamenei and khomeinis son 
ahmed khomeini or a turn to democracy 
given the weakness of the regime i think the turn to 
democracy is the most probable banisadr said and in that case 
the death of khomeini would be like the death of franco and the 
beginning of democracy 
banisadr speaking from versailles outside of paris said 
khomeinis death makes it very probable that he will be able to 
return to iran before long and possibly become involved again in 
government 
massoud rajavi leader of the rebel peoples mujahadeen of iran 
predicted that very much like the shahs regime irans 
fundamentalist government would not survive the death of its 
spiritual leader 
the end of the regime has come and the new era for the freedom 
of the iranian people has started rajavi said in a radio 
broadcast from iraq that was quoted by alireza jafarzadeh a 
spokesman for the resistance group in washington dc 
ayatollah mehdi rouhani spiritual leader of the shiite moslem 
community in europe called on iranian defenders and opponents of 
the regime to form a united front 
the ayatollah is dead but the iranian people lives he said 
in paris i hope the courage of my people will let them build a 
regime more just than todays 
the son of the former shah of iran predicted trouble in his 
homeland and a us official familiar with policy in iran said he 
did not anticipate any drastice change in policy in tehran in 
the postkhomeini era 
the washington dcbased official said there was no question 
that iran will remain an islamic republic but just what kind of 
course theyre going to take wed be just guessing right now 
he was quite a figure for iran and its revolution theres 
been a power struggle recently but its not clear who is on top 
said the official speaking on condition of anonymity 
he said there were some indications that a collective leadership 
would rule iran while various individuals vied for power 
khomeini came to power after months of street protests and 
strikes that in february 1979 ousted shah mohammad reza pahlavi and 
ended 2500 years of monarchy 
the shah died in 1980 his son reza pahlavi who has lived in 
exile in europe and the united states as the pretender to the 
peacock throne saw trouble ahead 
the shah predicts a period of uncertainty turmoil and feuding 
among the factions said robert armao a spokesman in new york 
for the pahlavi family 
armao an adviser to the late shah said security reasons 
prohibited his revealing where reza pahlavi resides but said it 
was somewhere in the united states 
</TEXT>
